    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <title>The Shadow Stick Challenge</title>
        <statement>
            <p><em>Objective:</em> To discover that the ratio between an object's height and its shadow length remains constant at a specific time.</p>
            <p><em>Work in Groups</em></p>
            <p><em>What you need:</em></p>
            <ul>
                <li>3 or 4 objects of different heights (e.g., a pencil, a water bottle, a ruler, a meter stick).</li>
                <li>A long measuring tape or a meter rule.</li>
                <li>A flat, sunny area (outdoors or near a bright window).</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>What to do</em></p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p><em>The Measurement Phase</em></p>
                    <p>Place your objects upright on the flat ground. At the exact same time of day, measure the height of the object and the length of the shadow it casts.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><em>Record and Calculate</em></p>
                    <p>Fill in the table below with your measurements. After recording, calculate the value of <m>\frac{y}{x}</m> for each object.</p>
                    <table>
                        <title>Measurements and Ratios</title>
                        <tabular halign="left">
                            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                                <cell>Object</cell>
                                <cell>Height of Object (<m>y</m>) in cm</cell>
                                <cell>Length of Shadow (<m>x</m>) in cm</cell>
                                <cell>Ratio (<m>\frac{y}{x}</m>)</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Pencil</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Water Bottle</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Ruler</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Long Stick</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><em>The Constant Discovery</em></p>
                    <p>Look at your last column. Even though the heights and shadows were all different, what do you notice about the <em>Ratio</em> <m>\frac{y}{x}</m>?</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>In a direct variation, this ratio is your <em>Constant of Proportionality</em> <m>k</m>.</li>
                        <li>This means <m>y = kx</m>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><em>The "Hidden" Prediction</em></p>
                    <p>Use your calculated constant (<m>k</m>) to predict the height of a nearby tree or building just by measuring its shadow length.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Measure the tree's shadow: ______ cm.</li>
                        <li>Multiply by your constant (<m>k</m>): ______ <m>\times</m> ______.</li>
                        <li>Your estimated height: ______ cm.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><em>Share and Reflect</em></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><em>Discussion:</em> Why do we have to measure all shadows at the same time? What would happen to our "constant" if we waited two hours?</li>
                        <li><em>Conclusion:</em> Direct variation means that as one value changes, the other changes in a way that keeps the relationship (<m>k</m>) exactly the same.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><em>Key Rule:</em> If the ratio <m>\frac{y}{x}</m> is always the same, you have found a direct variation!</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

