    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <title>Key Takeaway: Direct Variation</title>
        <p>Direct variation is defined by a constant ratio between two variables. When one variable is multiplied by a factor, the other is multiplied by the same factor.</p>
        
        <p><em>1. The Mathematical Rule</em></p>
        <p>Mathematically, we express this as:</p>
        <p><m>y = kx</m></p>
        <p>Where:</p>
        <list>
            <title>Variable roles</title>
            <item><m>y</m> and <m>x</m> are the variables that change.</item>
            <item><m>k</m> is the constant of proportionality. It tells us exactly how much <m>y</m> changes for every 1 unit change in <m>x</m>.</item>
        </list>
        <p><em>2. The Graphical Signature</em></p>
        <p>The graph of a direct variation relationship is always a straight line that passes through the origin <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>
        <list>
            <title>Graph facts</title>
            <item>The Slope is the Constant (<m>k</m>): The steepness of that line is exactly <m>k</m>. A larger <m>k</m> means a steeper line; a smaller <m>k</m> means a flatter line.</item>
            <item>The Origin <m>(0,0)</m>: If <m>x=0</m>, then <m>y</m> must be <m>0</m>. If a graph does not pass through the origin, it is <em>not</em> a direct variation.</item>
        </list>
        <p><em>3. Example: The Circumference of a Circle</em></p>
        <p>Geometry provides the perfect real-world example of direct variation. The formula for the circumference (<m>C</m>) of a circle is:</p>
        <p><m>C = \pi d</m></p>
        <p>(Where <m>d</m> is the diameter and <m>\pi</m> is the mathematical constant <m>\approx 3.14</m>)</p>
        <p>Comparing to <m>y = kx</m>:</p>
        <list>
            <title>Correspondence</title>
            <item><m>C</m> corresponds to <m>y</m>.</item>
            <item><m>d</m> corresponds to <m>x</m>.</item>
            <item><m>\pi</m> corresponds to <m>k</m>.</item>
        </list>
        
        <p><em>Why this is direct variation:</em></p>
        <p>If you double the diameter of a circle, the circumference doubles. If you triple the diameter, the circumference triples. Because <m>\pi</m> never changes, the ratio of <m>\frac{C}{d}</m> is always exactly <m>\pi</m>.</p>
        
        <p><em>Quick Summary for Learners</em></p>
        <table>
            <title>Direct Variation Features</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Feature</cell>
                    <cell>Direct Variation Rule</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Equation</cell>
                    <cell><m>y = kx</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Graph Shape</cell>
                    <cell>Perfectly straight line</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Origin Point</cell>
                    <cell>Must pass through <m>(0,0)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>The Constant <m>k</m></cell>
                    <cell>The constant ratio <m>\frac{y}{x}</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        
        <p>Direct variation is simply a relationship where everything stays balanced. If you increase your input, your output increases by the exact same proportion, every single time.</p>
    </insight>

