    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The amount of fuel (<m>F</m>) used by a generator varies directly as the number of hours (<m>h</m>) it runs. If the generator consumes 4 liters of fuel in 2 hours, calculate the fuel used in 7 hours.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><m>F \propto h</m></p>
            <p><m>\therefore F = kh</m></p>
            <p><em>Find the constant</em> <m>k</m>:</p>
            <p>Substituting <m>F = 4</m> when <m>h = 2</m></p>
            <p><m>4 = k \times 2</m></p>
            <p><m>k = \frac{4}{2} = 2</m></p>
            <p><em>Form the equation:</em></p>
            <p><m>F = 2h</m></p>
            <p><em>Calculate for</em> <m>h = 7</m>:</p>
            <p><m>F = 2 \times 7 = 14 \text{ liters}</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The extension (<m>e</m>) of a spring varies directly as the force (<m>F</m>) applied to it. A force of 10 Newtons causes an extension of 2 cm. Find the extension when a force of 25 Newtons is applied.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><m>e \propto F</m></p>
            <p><m>\therefore e = kF</m></p>
            <p><em>Find the constant</em> <m>k</m>:</p>
            <p>Substituting <m>e = 2</m> when <m>F = 10</m></p>
            <p><m>2 = k \times 10</m></p>
            <p><m>k = \frac{2}{10} = \frac{1}{5} = 0.2</m></p>
            <p><em>Form the equation:</em></p>
            <p><m>e = 0.2F</m></p>
            <p><em>Calculate for</em> <m>F = 25</m>:</p>
            <p><m>e = 0.2 \times 25 = 5 \text{ cm}</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The total pay (<m>P</m>) received by a part-time worker is directly proportional to the number of days (<m>d</m>) worked. If the worker earns 3,600 sh. for 3 days of work, how much will they earn for 10 days?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><m>P \propto d</m></p>
            <p><m>\therefore P = kd</m></p>
            <p><em>Find the constant</em> <m>k</m>:</p>
            <p>Substituting <m>P = 3600</m> when <m>d = 3</m></p>
            <p><m>3600 = k \times 3</m></p>
            <p><m>k = \frac{3600}{3} = 1200</m></p>
            <p>(This is the daily rate)</p>
            <p><em>Form the equation:</em></p>
            <p><m>P = 1200d</m></p>
            <p><em>Calculate for</em> <m>d = 10</m>:</p>
            <p><m>P = 1200 \times 10 = 12,000 \text{ sh.}</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The table below shows the amount of interest (<m>I</m>) earned on a savings account over a period of months (<m>m</m>).</p>
            <table>
                <title>Monthly Savings Interest</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Months (<m>m</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell>10</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Interest (<m>I</m>) in sh.</cell>
                        <cell>50</cell>
                        <cell>100</cell>
                        <cell>150</cell>
                        <cell>200</cell>
                        <cell>250</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
    
                <item>
                    <p>(a) Draw the graph representing this information.</p>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <p>(b) Use the graph to find the constant of proportionality.</p>
                </item>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>From the graph, we pick two points to find the gradient: <m>(4, 100)</m> and <m>(8, 200)</m>.</p>
            <p><m>\text{Gradient} = \frac{200 - 100}{8 - 4} = \frac{100}{4} = 25</m></p>
            <p><m>\text{Gradient} = \frac{I}{m} = 25</m></p>
            <p><m>I = 25m</m> is the equation relating <m>I</m> and <m>m</m>, and <em>25</em> is the constant of proportionality.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The table below shows the weight (<m>W</m>) of a liquid in grams compared to its volume (<m>V</m>) in cubic centimeters.</p>
            <table>
                <title>Liquid Weight and Volume</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Volume (<m>V</m>) in cm<m>^3</m></cell>
                        <cell>5</cell>
                        <cell>10</cell>
                        <cell>15</cell>
                        <cell>20</cell>
                        <cell>25</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Weight (<m>W</m>) in g</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell>12</cell>
                        <cell>16</cell>
                        <cell>20</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            
                <item>
                    <p>(a) Draw the graph representing this information.</p>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <p>(b) Use the graph to find the constant of proportionality.</p>
                </item>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>From the graph, we pick two points to find the gradient: <m>(10, 8)</m> and <m>(20, 16)</m>.</p>
            <p><m>\text{Gradient} = \frac{16 - 8}{20 - 10} = \frac{8}{10} = 0.8</m></p>
            <p><m>\text{Gradient} = \frac{W}{V} = 0.8</m></p>
            <p><m>W = 0.8V</m> is the equation relating <m>W</m> and <m>V</m>, and <em>0.8</em> (the density of the liquid) is the constant of proportionality.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

